<https://colonial-heritage.triply.cc/nmvw/id/object/RV-3025-60> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#material> "tekening op papier, gedeeltelijk met dunne laagjes waterverf bewerkt\r\n\r\n Coloured drawing made on a vasli or laminated support of several sheets of Indian handemade paper pasted together. \r\nThe primary outlines were made with charcoal, the secondary with red ink and the final composition with black ink. A layer of white primer was applied on the background and the colours started to be applied in light coloured washes (red, yellow, blue, green, carmine and purple).Two ruling were traced around the painting with a pen and a ruler.\r\nIn the top left edge, there are two letters written in black ink and in the bottom left corner, three numbers were penned as well. Workshop traces: traces of colour and brush, stains and smudges.\r\nThe verso bears handwritten annotations, Rs/3 (price in Rupees), no.11, and letters in landa script ( a language used among the business in Punjab to record accountings) as well as attribution to the painted figures: ‘Raja Amir Hath playing Holi with his Rani’. \r\nIt is likely that the piece was bought from Radha Krishna Bharany’s shop in Amritsar. The annotations and prices correspond to similar information found on other items of the collection. For further information, see, A Passionate Eye: Textiles, Painting and Sculpture from the Bharany Collections, 2014, The Marg Foundation.\r\nModern label at verso with title and description in Dutch of the image." .
